Impact: “Preliminary estimates place at Damage toll in Fayette County at $2.7 million, with $1.5 million for property and $1.2 million incurred to agriculture.”

Impact: “In Starr County, 4.7 in (120 mm) of precipitation fell in only about 90 minutes. Several low-lying streets were inundated by water, damaging dozens of vehicles. Some residents evacuated as water began entering homes.”

Impact: “In Brooks County peaked at 7.67 in (195 mm) in Falfurrias. The lowest-lying portions of the town were flooded after the Cibolo Creek swelled its bank, with water entering homes and businesses.”
Impact: “Between 4 and 6.5 in (100 and 170 mm) of precipitation fell overnight in Goliad County on August 30, flooding some farmlands after small creeks overflowed.”
Impact: “In Karnes County ... 16.29 in (414 mm) of rain fell ... Kenedy suffered extensive Damage ... at least 200 heads of cattle were killed. Damage reached approximately $5 million.”
Impact: “In Bastrop and Caldwell counties, a number of farms in rural areas were flooded after several creeks and streams overflowed.”
Impact: “In Bastrop and Caldwell counties, a number of farms in rural areas were flooded after several creeks and streams overflowed.”

Impact: “The community of Hochheim in DeWitt County observed around 17.5 in (440 mm) of precipitation ... Damage in the county reached $2.4 million, including $1.4 million to property and $1.2 million to agriculture.”

Impact: “In Gonzales County ... water from the rapidly swelling Tinsley Creek Damaged approximately 30 homes ... about 50 homes and mobile homes in Waelder were flooded ... Damage in the county was estimated at over $5 million.”
Impact: “Lavaca County suffered the worst impact from the storm ... with Damage reaching approximately $35 million.”

Impact: “Portions of Fort Bend County received over 10 in (250 mm) of rain ... some homes in low-lying areas south of Katy were flooded ... More than 1,000 acres of fields of harvestable cotton were inundated.”

Impact: “Rainfall totals of 6 to 11 in (150 to 280 mm) in much of Harris County elevated a number of bayous and creeks, some of which exceeded their banks. Across the county, several dozen businesses, 1,250 homes, and 1,000 vehicles were Damaged.”

Impact: “In Galveston County, several major streets in Galveston, Hitchcock, La Marque, and Texas City were flooded ... dozens of dwellings in low-lying areas ... The La Marque City Hall was also Damaged.”

Total_Summary_Affected.Total_Affected_Annotation: header: 2020 East Africa floods: 'The 2020 East Africa floods were a natural disaster in Rwanda, Kenya, Somalia, Burundi, Ethiopia, Uganda, Democratic Republic of Congo, Djibouti and Tanzania, affecting at least 700,000 people.'
